IMF Needs More Lagarde
Davos - Lagarde once said she was open to serving another five years as Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay on.
The IMF has never had better leadership than her, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting an institution in crisis.
The 2008 global financial crash and its economic aftermath discredited Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus".
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF restore its reputation.
Many have looked to her personal qualities — rightly so.
She is candid, strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from various countries (often meeting in delicate situations) have expressed that she is unafraid to state difficult realities while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate terms of agreements rather than dominate them.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else firewalls had to be built to prevent financial contagion. It was harsh advice, but Europeans followed it.
Similarly, she strongly urged providing IMF support to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which was crucial for global stability.
There are countless more examples.
The IMF is not known for innovation and is usually not passionate.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave this institution, which often prescribes bitter medicine, a more humane face.
For example, helping manage the Middle East refugee crisis was not originally within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million people live in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available funds to provide debt relief to countries affected by the crisis, enabling them to improve the pay of doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF used its capital in such a way.
Moreover, Lagarde recognized that the world today faces three of the most important challenges and took action on them.
First, she strongly advocated for more women to join the workforce, and she herself is a role model demonstrating the value of women in leadership positions.
In various countries from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a huge human resource — and thereby realize economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a basic issue of fairness.
IMF's research emphasizes that reducing the wealth gap is directly linked to increasing economic growth.
IMF is not the first institution to prove this point, but its position makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde personally has been committed to promoting this point, which is key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Lagarde has played an important role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change — some of which will cause frightening disruptive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase efficiency in manufacturing and reduce its costs, but it also means that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be less than before.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde has made the IMF the core of this work.
Critics would say it is time for a representative from a developing country to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European to hold this position in a row, and with Europe holding such privileges, it is difficult to gain credibility in today's world.
Some would also say that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not produced significant results, proving that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Others would point out that she faces allegations related to financial scandals in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
After her predecessor, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, was deeply involved in a scandal, critics argue that the IMF must never again be distracted by similar events.
Let us examine these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
But the goal of ending this Western privilege is to ensure that the leader selection process is based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for the IMF's Managing Director, and the emerging powers such as the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not jointly proposed an alternative candidate.
Having a European serve as the IMF's Managing Director might also have been a favorable factor in the IMF's decision last year to include the Chinese yuan in the currency basket that determines the value of its special drawing rights.
Furthermore, Lagarde ultimately convinced both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress with impressive political flexibility to approve IMF governance reforms, which not only enhanced the IMF's arsenal for containing financial crises but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS countries have now entered the top ten shareholder ranks of the IMF.
On the Greek issue, Lagarde made some forthright — which some might consider inappropriate — comments with her personal style last year.
But she is certainly not the culprit behind the economic pain suffered by the Greeks; her tenure at the IMF has fully demonstrated that no Managing Director in IMF history has done so much to lead the IMF in efforts to alleviate the suffering of people in crisis.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde in France were opposed by the French Chief Prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven that she is exactly such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF for the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to see her work through from start to finish.
